Objection Detection¶

Background¶

  • Ever since Alex Krizhevsky et al. won ImageNet in 2012, CNNs have become the gold standard for image classification.

  • In classification, there's generally an image with a single object as the focus and the task is to say what that image is.

  • But when we look at the world around us, we carry out far more complex tasks.

Source: https://blog.athelas.com/a-brief-history-of-cnns-in-image-segmentation-from-r-cnn-to-mask-r-cnn-34ea83205de4

  • We see complicated sights with multiple overlapping objects and different backgrounds
    • We not only classify these objects
    • but also identify:
      • their boundaries
      • their differences
      • and relations to one another.

Can CNNs help us with such complex tasks?

  • Namely, given a more complicated image, can we use CNNs to identify the different objects in the image, and their boundaries?
  • As has been shown by Ross Girshick and his peers over the last 3 years,

The answer is conclusively YES

Goal of this talk¶

  • Cover the intuition behind some of the main techniques used in object detection and segmentation

    • See how they've evolved from one implementation to the next

  • Cover

    • R-CNN(Regional CNN) and its descendants
    • Fast R-CNN,
    • Faster R-CNN, and finally
    • Mask R-CNN

Here are the papers referenced in this talk:

  • R-CNN: https://arxiv.org/abs/1311.2524
  • Fast R-CNN: https://arxiv.org/abs/1504.08083
  • Faster R-CNN: https://arxiv.org/abs/1506.01497
  • Mask R-CNN: https://arxiv.org/abs/1703.06870

2014: R-CNN - An Early Application of CNNs to Object Detection¶

To what extent do [Krizhevsky et. als results] generalize to object detection?

  • Object detection is the task of finding the different objects in an image and classifying them.

Understanding R-CNN¶

  • The goal of R-CNN is to take in an image, and correctly identify where the main objects (via a bounding box) in the image.

    • Inputs: Image
    • Outputs: Bounding boxes + labels for each object in the image.

  • But how do we find out where these bounding boxes are?

    • Propose a bunch of boxes in the image and see if any of them actually correspond to an object.

  • R-CNN creates these bounding boxes, or region proposals, using a process called Selective Search (http://www.cs.cornell.edu/courses/cs7670/2014sp/slides/VisionSeminar14.pdf)

  • At a high level, Selective Search looks at the image through windows of different sizes, and for each size tries to group together adjacent pixels by:

    • texture
    • color
    • or intensity

  • In step 3, R-CNN passes the warped region to a modified version of AlexNet
  • In step 4, on the final layer fo the CNN, R-CNN adds a Support Vector Machine(SVM) to classify whether this is an object, and if so what object.

Improving the Bounding Boxes¶

  • To tighten the bounding box to fit the true dimensions fo the object, we run a simple linear regressionn on the region proposal.

  • Here are the inputs and outputs of this regression model:

    • Inputs: sub-regions of the image corresponding to objects.
    • Outputs: New bounding box coordinates for the object in the sub-region.

So, to summarize, R-CNN is just the following steps:

  1. Generate a set of proposals for bounding boxes.

  2. Run the images in the bounding boxes through a pre-trained AlexNet and finally an SVM to see what object the image in the box is.

  3. Run the box through a linear regression model to output tighter coordinates for the box once the object has been classified.

Image source: http://cs231n.stanford.edu/slides/2017/cs231n_2017_lecture11.pdf

2015: Fast R-CNN - Speeding up and Simplifying R-CNN¶

Image source: http://cs231n.stanford.edu/slides/2017/cs231n_2017_lecture11.pdf

Fast R-CNN Insight 1: RoI(Region of Interest) Pooling¶

  • Just run the CNN just once per image and then find a way to share that computation across the ~ 2000 proposals

  • So, all it takes us is one pass fo the original image to generate region proposals as opposed to ~2000.

Fast R-CNN Insight 2: Combine All models into One Network¶

  • Jointly train the CNN, classifier, and bounding box regressor in a single model. R-CNN uses different models to extract iamge features (CNN), classify (SVM), and tighten bouding boxes (regressor), Fast R-CNN instead uses a single network to compute all three.

Image source: http://cs231n.stanford.edu/slides/2017/cs231n_2017_lecture11.pdf

2016: Faster R-CNN - Speeding Up Region Proposal¶

Why not reuse the same CNN results for region proposals instead of running a separate selective search algorithm?

2017: Mask R-CNN - Extending Faster R-CNN for Pixel Level Segmentation¶

  • Can we extend the above techniques to go one step further and locate exact pixels of each object instead of just bounding boxes?

Mask R-CNN: Very Good Results! Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/1703.06870

Configurations¶

We will be using a model trained on the MS-COCO dataset. The configurations of this model in the CocoConfig class in coco.py.

For inferencing, modify the configurations a bit to fit the task. To do do, sub-class the CocoConfig class and override the attributes you need to change.

In [7]:
class InferenceConfig(coco.CocoConfig):
    # Set batch size to 1 since we will be running inference on one image a
    # a time. Batch size = GPU_COUNT * IMAGES_PER_GPU
    GPU_COUNT = 1
    IMAGES_PER_GPU = 1
    
config = InferenceConfig()
config.print()

Class Names¶

The model classifies objects and returns class IDs, which are integer value that identify each class. Some datasets assign integer values to their classes and some don't. For example, in the MS-COCO dataset, the 'person' class is 1 and 'teddy bear' is 88. The IDs are often sequential, but not always. The COCO dataset, for example, has classes associated with class IDs 70 and 72, but not 71.

To improve consistency, and to support training on data from multiple sources at the same time, our Dataset class assigns it's own sequential integer IDs to each class. For example, if you load the COCO dataset using our Dataset class, the 'person' class would get class ID = 1 (just like COCO) and the 'teddy bear' class is 78 (different from COCO). Keep that in mind when mapping class IDs to class names.

To get the list of class names, you'd load the dataset and then use the class_names property like this.

# Load COCO dataset
dataset = coco.CocoDataset()
dataset.load_coco(COCO_DIR, "train")
dataset.prepare()

# Print class names
print(dataset.class_names)

We don't want to require you to download the COCO dataset just to run this demo, so we're including the list of class names below. The index of the class name in the list represent its ID (first class is 0, second is 1, third is 2, ...etc.)

Run Object Detection¶

In [15]:
# Load a random image from the images folder
file_names = next(os.walk(IMAGE_DIR))[2]
image = scipy.misc.imread(os.path.join(IMAGE_DIR, random.choice(file_names)))

# Run detection
results = model.detect([image], verbose=1)

# Visualize results
r = results[0]
visualize.display_instances(image, r['rois'], r['masks'], r['class_ids'], 
                            class_names, r['scores'])

Key Take Aways:¶

  • Seen in isolation, results like Mask R-CNN seem like incredible leaps of genius that would be unapproachable.
  • Yet, throughout this presentation, I hope you've seen how such advancements are really the sum of intuitive, incremental improvements through years of hard work and collaboration
